   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE introduction "1. Introduction"

@{b}1. Introduction@{ub}

  CED_HTML has been realized to help people who want to write HTML v3.2
  documents with CygnusED v4.2. CED_HTML is composed by several AREXX
  scripts which can be started using a main script. You can add this
  main script to CED's pull-down menus and reach all scripts of this
  package by entering it's number.

  If you don't know HTML v3.2 syntax, CED_HTML won't help you. CED_HTML
  isn't an HTML v3.2 documentation nor a "plug and play" solution. 
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE status "2. Status"

@{b}2. Status@{ub}

  Freeware.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE requirements "3. Requirements"

@{b}3. Requirements@{ub}

  * Amiga

  * CygnusED v4.2. (older versions untested)

  * RexxMast running

  * Basic knowledge of HTML v3.2
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE installation "4. Installation"

@{b}4. Installation@{ub}

  Installation of CED_HTML is done easily by following the steps listed
  here.

  If you have "Installer" somewhere in your path (e.g. in C:) you can
  use the Installer script supplied with CED_HTML and skip the steps 1
  and 2.

    1 - Copy the directory "Html" to where ever you want, e.g. to your CED
        directory, REXX: or kind of. If you are using the Installer
        script, you will be prompted to backup an older version of this
        drawer if one is found in your installation path.

    2 - Enter the line:
                  Assign "CED_HTML:" "YourPersonalPath/Html"
        in a shell window for temporary usage and/or in your user-startup
        for a permanent installation (replace "YourPersonalPath" with the
        dir you copied the drawer "Html" before). If you don't want this
        assign in your s:user-startup, you can also use the "Make_Assign"
        script from this package which will ask you for the path of the
        "Html" drawer with a requester.

    3 - Start CygnusED

    4 - Select "Install command DOS/AREXX" from CygnusED's pull-down menus,
        enter a number from 1 to 10 to the upcoming requester in order to
        select one of the F1 ... F10 keys for this command. As the command
        to execute with this key enter "CED_HTML:cedmacros.ced" to the
        second requester.

    5 - Select "Save command DOS/AREXX" from the pull-down menus if you want
        CED_HTML to be installed permanently.

  That's all.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE usage "5. Usage"

@{b}5. Usage@{ub}

  To start CED_HTML, simply press the key you have assigned the cedmacros.ced
  script to (one of the F1 ... F10 keys). If you can't remember the key, take
  a look at the DOS/AREXX menu, where it should be listed. You can also start
  CED_HTML by selecting it from this pull-down menu.

  A requester should appear, showing you a list of all scripts supplied with
  CED_HTML. You should remember the number of the script you wish to start
  and either click at the "OK" button or press your return key. A second
  requester will ask you to enter the script number then.

  In general the CED_HTML scripts will open some more requesters asking you to
  select between several options or to enter parameters the script should use.
  Finally most of the scripts will output one or several lines of HTML v3.2
  code at current cursor position, saving you lots of time for entering them
  by hand.

  @{b}Some words about the requesters@{ub}

  The requesters of CED_HTML behave in the manner you should be familar with
  when you ever tried other requesters of CED or the famous ReqTools
  requesters. They will always appear next to your mouse pointer position and
  most of them will have an "OK" and a "Cancel" button. You can select those
  buttons with your keyboard by pressing either the return or the escape key.
  Whenever you select "Cancel", the execution of the entire CED_HTML script
  will be abandoned.

  All requesters have a default input which you will select by just pressing
  return without making any other input. You can easily delete the initial
  input of a requester by pressing shift and delete (erases everything right
  to cursor position). Other popular keyboard options like shift-backspace
  (delete everything to the left) or shift-cursor_right (jump to end of line)
  and so on will also work with CED_HTML. Nearly all requesters do a little
  check for correct input and will repeat to come up until you gave one or
  choose to select "Cancel". However, when you enter nothing at all to a
  requester asking for a text input, the whole script will be abandoned.

  @{b}Formatted output with indent function@{ub}

  It is one of the main goals of this package to output HTML source which is
  easy to read, so starting and ending tags of HTML commands are placed in
  single lines and other input (e.g. text) will be indented with a tab. The
  scripts also support CED's auto-indent feature: If the cursor position is
  indented with tabs or spaces when starting a CED_HTML script, these tabs
  and spaces are added to the indent the script does. You will find this
  feature useful whenever you add more HTML commands to a source part where
  the text already is indented.

  That's also why at the end of a script output the cursor is always placed
  directly after the last word of output. Your well formated source is just a
  shift-return away...

  @{b}Script details@{ub}

  The following chapters contain more information about purpose and usage
  of every single script. You can flip through all of them with the forward
  button or pick one topic from this overview. The HTML commands right to
  the button should give you a quick idea what the script will do.

  01 @{" Main structure      " link "structure" } <HTML><HEAD><META...></HEAD> <BODY..>...
  02 @{" Title               " link "title"     } <H1> ... <H6 ALIGN="...">
  03 @{" Font options        " link "font"      } <FONT SIZE="..." COLOR="...">
  04 @{" Text aspect         " link "aspect"    } <I>, <B>, <U>, <SUB>, <SMALL>, <CODE>,...
  05 @{" Paragraph           " link "paragraph" } <P ALIGN="...">...</P>
  06 @{" Sub paragraph       " link "sub"       } <DIV ALIGN="...">
  07 @{" List structure      " link "list"      } <UL> or <OL TYPE="..." START="..."><LI>...
  08 @{" List item           " link "item"      } <LI>...
  09 @{" Glossary structure  " link "glossary"  } <DL><DT></DT><DD></DD>...</DL>
  10 @{" Glossary item       " link "glossitem" } <DT></DT><DD></DD>...
  11 @{" New line            " link "newline"   } <BR> or <WBR>
  12 @{" No new line         " link "nonewline" } <NOBR>unwrapped text</NOBR>
  13 @{" Horizontal bar      " link "bar"       } <HR WIDTH="..." ALIGN="..." NOSHADE>
  14 @{" Comment             " link "comments"  } <!-- Comment in source code -->
  15 @{" Remove all comments " link "remcomm"   } Delete <!-- Comments -->
