   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE structure "5.01. Main structure"

@{b}5.01 Main structure@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          1

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a basic HTML page. In addition, some <META> tags and options
          for the <BODY> tag can be entered directly to requesters.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">

          <HTML>

            <HEAD>
             <TITLE>
              Should be modified - Window title
             </TITLE>

             <META NAME="Description" CONTENT="@{b}user input@{ub}">
             <META NAME="Keywords" CONTENT="@{b}user input@{ub}">
             <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="@{b}user input@{ub}">
             <META NAME="Machine" CONTENT="Amiga">
             <META NAME="Generator" CONTENT="CygnusED Pro v4.2 with Ced_Html v2.2">
           </HEAD>

           <BODY BGCOLOR=#808080 TEXT=#000000 LINK=#0000FF VLINK=#FF0000 ALINK=#FFFFFF>

             Should be modified - Page content

           </BODY>

          </HTML>

          ------
          (Bold fields will contain user input to the corresponding requester.)

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter a text for the <META NAME=Description> tag to the first
          requester. This tag is mainly used by some search engines to place
          this text as a short info about your page instead of showing the
          first few lines.

          Enter one or several keywords, separated by commas, for the <META
          NAME=Keywords> tag. This one can be used to make a few search
          engines list your page higher in the list of hits, when the search
          expression is also found in here.

          Then enter your name for the <META NAME=Author> tag.

          Enter a "y" to the requester for main color options if you wish to
          insert color settings to your <BODY> Tag. Type "n" if you do not wish
          to insert anything at all or "d" if you wish to use the following
          default settings (which you can change in html_main.ced manually):

                  BGCOLOR = "#808080"
                  TEXT = "#000000"
                  LINK = "#0000FF"
                  VLINK = "#FF0000"
                  ALINK = "#FFFFFF"

          If you have chosen "y" before, you will be asked to press "c" to enter
          a color for the background or "i" to use an image. You will be either
          asked to enter a #RGB color code (don't forget the leading "#") or
          to enter a local, absolute or universal path for your background image.
          After that you will be asked for #RGBs for the other colors.

          At the end, a last requester asks you if you want to erase the file
          contents. If your answer is negative, the output of the "Main
          structure" script will be placed at the beginning of the file without
          discarding anything. Otherwise every old text in your CED window will
          be deleted.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE title "5.02. Title"

@{b}5.02 Title@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          2

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a headline of font size 1 to 6 using <H1> ... <H6> and
          add an alignment to it.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <H1 ALIGN=LEFT>
           Should be modified - Title
          </H1>
          ---
          <H3 ALIGN=RIGHT>
           Should be modified - Title
          </H3>
          ---
          <H6 ALIGN=CENTER>
           Should be...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter a font size to the first requester. "1" is for greatest, "6"
          for smallest font size of the headline.

          Enter a position for your title into the second, either "l", "r" or
          "c" for left, right or center.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE font "5.03. Font options"

@{b}5.03 Font options@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          3

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Change font size and color for some text.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <FONT SIZE=1 COLOR=#000000>
           Should be modified - Font Options
          </FONT>
          ---
          <FONT SIZE=7 COLOR=#FFFFFF>
           Should be...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter the font size for your text to the requester, "1" is for smallest,
          "7" for greatest size. Note that default HTML font size is "3".

          Enter a color for your text to the second requester. You have to use
          the format #RGB and should not forget the leading "#". If nothing is
          entered, the default of "#000000" (black) is used.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE aspect "5.04. Text aspect"

@{b}5.04 Text aspect@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          4

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a text block with a special text style.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <I>
           Should be modified - Text aspect
          </I>
          ---
          <B>
           Should be modified - Text aspect
          </B>
          ---
          etc.

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter one of the numbers from "1" to "17" for the following text styles:

             (1)  - default
             (2)  - italic           <I> ... </I>
             (3)  - bold             <B> ... </B>
             (4)  - underline        <U> ... </U>
             (5)  - subscript        <SUB> ... </SUB>
             (6)  - superscript      <SUP> ... </SUP>
             (7)  - small            <SMALL> ... </SMALL>
             (8)  - big              <BIG> ... </BIG>
             (9)  - strike           <STRIKE> ... </STRIKE>
            (10)  - definition       <DFN> ... </DFN>
            (11)  - sample           <SAMP> ... </SAMP>
            (12)  - variable         <VAR> ... </VAR>
            (13)  - source code      <CODE> ... </CODE>
            (14)  - citation         <CITE> ... </CITE>
            (15)  - teletype         <TT> ... </TT>
            (16)  - keybord          <KBD> ... </KBD>
            (17)  - URL              <ADDRESS> ... </ADDRESS>
            (18)  - formated text    <PRE> ... </PRE>
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE paragraph "5.05. Paragraph"

@{b}5.05 Paragraph@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          5

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a new paragraph with either left, center or right aligning.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <P ALIGN=LEFT>
           Should be modified - Paragraph
          </P>
          ---
          <P ALIGN=RIGHT>
           Should be modified - Paragraph
          </P>
          ---
          <P ALIGN=CENTER>
           Should be...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter a "l", "c" or "r" to the requester for the position of your new
          paragraph.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE sub "5.06. Sub paragraph"

@{b}5.06 Sub paragraph@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          6

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a sub paragraph and choose it's alignment.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <DIV ALIGN=LEFT>
           Should be modified - SubParagraph
          </DIV>
          ---
          <DIV ALIGN=CENTER>
           Should be modified - SubParagraph
          </DIV>
          ---
          <DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>
           Should be...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          You will be prompted to enter the alignment of your sub paragraph.
          Choose either "l", "c" or "r" for left, center or right.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE list "5.07. List structure"

@{b}5.07 List structure@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          7

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate a list of several items, either using the default list type
          or a counting type with any start value you want.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <UL>
           <LI>
            <!-- Comment - Item 1 -->
            Should be modified
           </LI>
           <LI>
            <!-- Comment - Item 2 -->
            Should be modified
           </LI>
           ...
          </UL>
          ---
          <OL TYPE=A START=3>
           <LI>
            <!-- Comment - Item 1 -->
            Should be modified
           </LI>
           ...
          </OL>
          ---
          etc.

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          A small requester gives you an overview of the list types available.
          Press return or select "OK" to continue.

          Select the type of your list by entering one of the following chars to
          the next requester:

                  (d)efault
                  (a)rabic  1,2,3,...
                  (l)etter  a,b,c,...
                  (L)etter  A,B,C,...
                  (r)oman   i,ii,iii,...
                  (R)oman   I,II,III,...

          "Default" means the standard list with <UL>, where all items are
          not numbered. All others are realised with <OL>.

          Then you will be prompted for the number of items your list should
          contain. If you selected one of the letter types ("l" or "L") the
          maximum number of items is 26, else 32768. The default is "3".

          If you did not select the default type, a last requester will ask you
          for the start value of list items.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          You can add more list items afterwards by using the @{" List item " link "item"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE item "5.08. List item"

@{b}5.08 List item@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          8

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Add more <LI> items to an existing list.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <LI>
            <!-- Comment - New item 1 -->
            Should be modified
          </LI>
          <LI>
            <!-- Comment - New item 2 -->
            Should be modified
          </LI>
          <LI>
          ...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter the number of items you need to the requester. Valid are values
          from 1 to 32768, default is 2.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          You can insert a complete list structure with the @{" List structure " link "list"}
          script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE glossary "5.09. Glossary structure"

@{b}5.09 Glossary structure@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          9

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a list of notations and definitions for them.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <DL>
            <DT>
             <!-- Comment - Item 1 -->
             Should be modified
            </DT>	
            <DD>
             <!-- Comment - Definition 1 -->
             Should be modified
            </DD>	
             ...
          </DL>	

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter the number of items for your list at the first requester. Valid
          values are all numbers from "0" to "32768", default is "2". The script will
          generate a pair of <DL></DL> and as many <DT></DT> and <DD></DD> pairs
          between them as you requested.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          You can add more items afterwards by using the @{" Glossary item " link "glossitem"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE glossitem "5.10. Glossary item"

@{b}5.10 Glossary item@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          10

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Add more notations and descriptions for them to an existing glossary.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <DT>
            <!-- Comment - New item 1 -->
            Should be modified
          </DT>
          <DD>
            <!-- Comment - New definition 1 -->
            Should be modified
          </DD>
          <DT>
            <!-- Comment - New item 2 -->
            Should be modified
          </DT>
          <DD>
            <!-- Comment - New definition 1 -->
            Should be modified
          </DD>
          ...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter the number of item and definition pairs you wish to add to your
          glossary. Valid are values from 1 to 32768, default is 2.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          You can insert a complete glossary structure with the @{" Glossary structure " link "glossary"}
          script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE newline "5.11. New line"

@{b}5.11 New line@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          11

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a linefeed or a forced linefeed, which even works in areas
          where text wrapping is not allowed.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <BR>
          ---
          <WBR>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter a "d" to insert a normal linefeed <BR> to your code or "s" to
          force a linefeed with <WBR>, even when text wrapping is not allowed
          in this text block.
  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          Areas without text wrapping can be defined with the @{" No new line " link "nonewline"}
          script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE nonewline "5.12. No new line"

@{b}5.12 No new line@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          12

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a block of text where no text wrapping is allowed.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <NOBR>
           Should be modified - No new line
          </NOBR>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          This script needs no parameters.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          In areas with text wrapping not allowed, <WBR> can be used to
          force a linefeed. You can insert it using the @{" New line " link "newline"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE bar "5.13. Horizontal bar"

@{b}5.13 Horizontal bar@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          13

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a horizontal bar of a user defined width, height and
          position. Optional remove the bar's shadow.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=2 ALIGN=CENTER>
          ---
          <HR WIDTH=400 SIZE=5 ALIGN=LEFT NOSHADE>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter the width of the bar to the first requester. The width
          may be defined as a number of pixels or as a percent value of
          the actual window width. Default is "100%" (full window width).

          After that you can enter the height of the bar in pixels which
          defaults to "2".

          You can choose to position the bar to the left, right or center
          by entering "l", "r" or "c" to the following requester.

          Optional you can add the keyword NOSHADE by answering "n" to the
          question, if your bar should have shadows.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE comments "5.14. Comment"

@{b}5.14 Comment@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          14

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a comment to your HTML source which will not be shown in
          the browser window.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <!-- Your comment text -->

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Simply enter your comment text to the requester.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          You can remove all comments in your HTML source with the
          @{" Remove all comments " link "remcomm"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE remcomm "5.15. Remove all comments"

@{b}5.15 Remove all comments@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          15

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Remove all comments from your HTML source code.
          
  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Answer "OK" to the requester if you wish to run the script.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
          At current state the script only deletes comments, which are placed
          in a single line with no other text in this line.

          The script is mainly thought as a solution for people who don't like
          some of CED_HTML's scripts to insert lots of comments to the source
          while other people might think it is helpful to have for example a
          small marker for lines and columns for each table cell generated by
          the @{" Table structure " link "table"} script.

          You can insert comments in your HTML source with the @{" Comment " link "comments"} script.

  @{b}Tip:@{ub}
          It is very easy to use this script to strip off all comments the
          CED_HTML scripts inserted but to leave all your own comments in the
          source: just write your own comments in a style the remove script does
          not recognize, e.g. use several lines for them like this:

                  <!--
                   This is a comment which will not be removed
                  -->
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE iso "5.16. Iso latin 1"

@{b}5.16 Iso latin 1@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          16

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Check the HTML body for special chars and replace them with their
          correspondending ASCII code in order to make the document viewable
          on all systems, independent from their individual charset depending
          of the country they were produced for.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          A HTML page with all critical chars replaced, e.g.
                  $  -->  &#36;
                  Ą  -->  &#165;
                  Ő  -->  &#213;
                  ß  -->  &#223;
                  ...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          The script needs no parameters. However, a complete ASCII table is
          included in this script where replacement of some characters is
          commented out and others are still active. It might be useful for you
          to change this to meet your personal needs, e.g. sometimes it might be
          useful also to translate &, ~, <, >, " and % which is currently
          disabled.

          Please be careful when editing this script! At current state only a
          check is made to prevent characters in the <HEAD> from being replaced.
          There is still no check if a special character is part of a HTML
          command, so enabling the replacement of e.g. < may screw up your
          source code because every < from HTML commands you entered before
          running this script will be replaced too.

          After replacing all special chars in the source, the script checks if
          a <TITLE> tag already has been added to the source code. If none is
          found, it will look for a <HEAD> command. If none of both can be found
          nothing more will be done by the script. Otherwise either after
          </TITLE> or <HEAD> the following <META> tag will be added:

          <META HTTP-EQUIV="Content-Type" CONTENT="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
          Running this script may take some time, depending on your CPU.

          There is no longer a need to insert <BODY> and </BODY> to your text
          before running this script as it was in former versions.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE center "5.17. Center"

@{b}5.17 Center@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          17

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Place one or several elements of your document at center position.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <CENTER>
           Should be modified - Center
          </CENTER>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          This script needs no parameters.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE table "5.18. Table structure"

@{b}5.18 Table structure@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          18

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Setting up the base parameters for a table. You can enter
          the number of columns and lines directly and optional change
          the global dimensions and colors, the dimensions, colors and
          alignments for your cells, insert a caption and replace a line or
          column of default cells <TD> with header cells <TH>.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <TABLE BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=5 WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% CELLPADDING=10
           BGCOLOR=#808080 BORDERCOLOR=#FFFFFF BORDERCOLORDARK=#303030
           BORDERCOLORLIGHT=#B0B0B0>
           <CAPTION VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER>
             Should be modified - Table caption
           </CAPTION>

           <TR>
            <!-- Comment - Line 1 -->
            <TH ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - Main cell (column 1) -->
              Should be modified
            </TH>
            <TH ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - Main cell (column 2) -->
              Should be modified
            </TH>
           </TR>
           <TR>
            <!-- Comment - Line 2 -->
            <TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - Default cell (column 1) -->
              Should be modified
            </TD>
            <TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - Default cell (column 2) -->
              Should be modified
            </TD>
           </TR>
          </TABLE>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Define a number of lines for your table using the first requester.
          Valid numbers are "0" to "32768", default is "2". When typing "0"
          no <TR> and <TD> tags will be added and just <TABLE ...> and
          </TABLE> tags will be generated.

          Then do the same for the number of columns. Again, the default is
          "2".

          The next requester will ask you if you would like to edit the
          options for the global dimensions of your table. By entering "y" you
          will be able to do this, "n" will not add any size options at all and a
          "d" will give you the following defaults, which you can change in the
          script itself:

                  BORDER = "5"
                  WIDTH = "100%"
                  HEIGHT = "100%"
                  CELLPADDING = "10"
                  CELLSPACING = "5"

          If you entered "y", requesters will come up asking you about the
          BORDER thickness in pixels, CELLSPACING in pixels, the over all
          WIDTH and HEIGHT of the table (both can be entered in pixels or
          in percentage of the window dimensions) and CELLPADDING in pixels.
          All values default to the values above.

          After this you will be asked if you would like to change the
          settings for the table colors. Again you can enter "y", "n" or
          "d". The default values are:

                  BGCOLOR = "#808080"
                  BorderColor = "#FFFFFF"
                  BorderColorDark = "#303030"
                  BorderColorLight = "#B0B0B0"

          If you entered "y" you can enter new #RGB values for the table
          background color, the border color, the bottom shade of the border
          and the top shade. Don't forget the leading "#"!

          After that you will be asked if you wish to modify the options for
          your cells. Enter "y" if you want to do this, "n" if your cells
          should contain no options at all or "d" for the following defaults:

                  ALIGN=CENTER
                  VALIGN=MIDDLE
                  WIDTH=100%
                  HEIGHT=100%
                  BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0

          If you entered "y" before, you will be asked if you wish to edit the
          cell options global (default) or individual. Enter either "g" or "i".
          If you decided to change the options global, you will be prompted
          once to enter a left, center or right alignment, a top, middle or
          bottom vertical alignment, width and height in either percentage or
          pixels and a #RGB for the background color. Your input will be used
          in all cells. If you selected the individual mode these steps will be
          repeated for every single cell.

          Then you can add a caption to your table by chosing a top position
          for this text (enter "t") or a bottom position (enter "b"). You can
          also enter "n" to insert no caption at all.

          If you entered a caption, you will then be prompted to enter an
          alignment for it, either "l", "c" or "r" for left, center or right.

          After this you can enter a position for table header cells. You can
          enter "l" to place all <TH> left, "r" for right, "t" for top, "b"
          for bottom or even "n" for not inserting <TH> cells instead of <TD>
          at all.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
          If you did not enter enough table header cells and table default
          cells, you can easily add more using the @{" Table cell " link "tc"} script.

          If you did not enter a <CAPTION>, you can use the @{" Table caption " link "caption"}
          script afterwards to add one.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE tc "5.19. Table cell"

@{b}5.19 Table cell@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          19

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert additional header and default cells to a table.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <TR>
            <!-- Comment - New line 1 -->
            <TH ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - New main cell (column 1) -->
              Should be modified
            </TH>
            <TD ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - New default cell (column 2) -->
              Should be modified
            </TD>
          </TR>
          <TR>
            <!-- Comment - New line 2 -->
            <TH ALIGN=CENTER VALIGN=MIDDLE WIDTH=100% HEIGHT=100% BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0>
              <!-- Comment - New main cell (column 1) -->
              Should be...
          ...

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Define how many new lines of table cells you wish to add using the first
          requester. Valid numbers are "1" to "32768", default is "2".

          Then do the same for the number of columns. Again, the default is
          "2".

          After that you will be asked if you wish to modify the options for
          your cells. Enter "y" if you want to do this, "n" if your cells
          should contain no options at all or "d" for the following defaults:

                  ALIGN=CENTER
                  VALIGN=MIDDLE
                  WIDTH=100%
                  HEIGHT=100%
                  BGCOLOR=#B0B0B0

          If you entered "y" before, you will be asked if you wish to edit the
          cell options global (default) or individual. Enter either "g" or "i".
          If you decided to change the options global, you will be prompted
          once to enter a left, center or right alignment, a top, middle or
          bottom vertical alignment, width and height in either percentage or
          pixels and a #RGB for the background color. Your input will be used
          in all cells. If you selected the individual mode these steps will be
          repeated for every single cell.

          After this you can enter a position for table header cells. You can
          enter "l" to place all <TH> left, "r" for right, "t" for top, "b"
          for bottom or even "n" for not inserting <TH> cells instead of <TD>
          at all.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          Additional table cells may only be used within a <TABLE>...</TABLE> tag.
          You can generate a basic table with the @{" Table structure " link "table"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE caption "5.20. Table caption"

@{b}5.20 Table caption@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          20

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Place a description text for a table at a position near to it.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <CAPTION VALIGN=BOTTOM ALIGN=CENTER>
           Should be modified - Table caption
          </CAPTION>
          ---
          <CAPTION VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT>
           Should be modified - Table caption
          </CAPTION>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Enter a "t" or "b" to the first requester to place the text about
          the table at the top or the bottom of your table.

          Enter "l", "r" or "c" to the second requester to place the text in
          left, right or centered position.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          <CAPTION> may only be used within a <TABLE>...</TABLE> tag. You can
          generate a basic table with the @{" Table structure " link "table"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE anchor "5.21. Anchor"

@{b}5.21 Anchor@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          21

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert an anchor to your document so this position can be reached
          directly via a link. The anchor can mark some text or also an image.
          If you select to insert an image anchor, the code for inserting the
          image will also be generated in the same way the @{" Image " link "image"} script does.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <A NAME="markername">
           Should be modified - Anchor text
          </A>
          ---
          <A NAME="begin_chapter3">
           <IMG SRC="image.iff" ALT="Here should be an image" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100
           HEIGHT=100 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
          </A>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          The first requester asks for the name of the new anchor.

          A second requester will ask if the anchor belongs to a text (enter
          "t") or an image (enter "i"). If you selected a text anchor you are
          finished now, otherwise some more requesters will ask you for the
          parameters to insert the image:

          Enter "l", "a" or "u" to the first image requester to tell the script
          whether the path to the image is local, absolute or universal.

          Then enter the path to the image which has to match the path type you
          selected before.

          The next requester asks you for the text which should be shown instead
          of the picture, when image loading is switched off or a text browser
          is used.

          Then you will be asked if you would like to modify the options for
          the image size. You may enter "y" if you want to do this, "n" if you
          do not want to enter any size options to the <IMG> tag or "d" to use
          the following default values:

                  WIDTH="100"
                  HEIGHT="100"
                  BORDER="0"

          If you entered "y" before, you will be asked to enter the image width
          in pixels, the image height in pixels and a border width in pixels.

          The next requester asks if you wish to modify the options for the image
          position. Again you can enter "y", "n" or "d". The default values are:

                  no align
                  HSPACE=10
                  VSPACE=10

          If you entered "y" you can select between left, right, center or no
          alignment by typing the first letter. Then you can enter the horizontal
          and vertical space in pixels between the image and the next elements of
          the document.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          To insert the code for a link to this anchor, you can make use of the
          @{" Link " link "link"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE map "5.22. Map structure"

@{b}5.22 Map structure@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          22

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate a map to use with an image and define the sensible areas.
          Optional this script inserts the image to use with this map the
          same way the @{" Image " link "image"} script does and allows you to add links to
          the different areas just like the @{" Link " link "link"} script. You
          can also generate a map to use with a CGIscript.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}

          <CENTER>
          <IMG SRC="image.iff" ALT="Here should be an image" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100
           HEIGHT=100 HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 USEMAP="#Mapname">
          </CENTER>

          <MAP NAME="Mapname">
            <AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="0,0,50,50" HREF="http://www.example.org/">
            <AREA SHAPE="CIRCLE" COORDS="40,40,30" HREF="next.html#chapter5">
            <AREA SHAPE="POLYGON" COORDS="0,0,0,40,40,40,40,0" HREF="mailto:me@here.org">
            ...
          </MAP>
          ---
          <A HREF="CGIscript.pl?dosomething&secondoption">
            <IMG SRC="image.jpg" ALT="Here is a map" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=100
             HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10 ISMAP>
          </A>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Select at first if you wish to generate the source code for a normal
          map (offline, enter "f") or if you wish to use a CGIscript to define
          sensible areas of your image (online, enter "n").

          If you decided to use a CGIscript by typing "n" you will at first be
          asked if you would like to generate the source code for inserting the
          image to use with the map. When answering "y" you will be prompted
          for the image options as described below. A <IMG> tag will be generated
          from your inputs and the ISMAP keyword will be added to it. After that
          you will be asked to enter a local, absolute or universal path and
          the name of your CGIscript which may be followed by options. You are
          finished here.

          If you selected an offline type of map by typing "f" (default), a
          requester will ask you, if you would like the script to insert
          the code for the image to use with your map directly. Enter either
          "y" or "n".

          If you entered "y" some more requesters will ask you for the image
          parameters:

            Enter "l", "a" or "u" to the first image requester to tell the
            script whether the path to the image is local, absolute or universal.

            Then enter the path to the image which has to match the path type
            you selected before.

            The next requester asks you for the text which should be shown
            instead of the picture, when image loading is switched off or a
            text browser is used.

            Then you will be asked if you would like to modify the options for
            the image size. You may enter "y" if you want to do this, "n" if
            you do not want to enter any size options to the <IMG> tag or "d"
            to use the following default values:

                  WIDTH="100"
                  HEIGHT="100"
                  BORDER="0"

            If you entered "y" before, you will be asked to enter the image
            width in pixels, the image height in pixels and a border width in
            pixels.

            The next requester asks if you wish to modify the options for the
            image position. Again you can enter "y", "n" or "d". The default
            values are:

                  no align
                  HSPACE=10
                  VSPACE=10

            If you entered "y" you can select between left, right, center or
            no alignment by typing the first letter. Then you can enter the
            horizontal and vertical space in pixels between the image and the
            next elements of the document.

            Then you will be asked for the name of the map to use with this
            image.

          If you have used the requesters before to insert an image for your
          map and also entered the image size options for it, you can directly
          specify the sensible areas of your map. Enter the number of areas
          you wish to create for your image map. When entering "0", no areas
          will be defined and just <MAP> and </MAP> will be inserted.

          A requester will show you a small help, how to define areas. After
          that you will be asked to enter the type and the dimensions of your
          areas. This part will be repeated for the number of areas you entered
          before:

          First select the type of your area. Enter "r" for rectangular, "c"
          for circle or "p" for polygon.

            @{b}1.@{ub} rectangular areas:
            If you entered an area to be rectangular, you will be prompted 4
            times to insert the coordinates in pixels for the area. Remember,
            the origin (0,0) of area coords is always at the upper left corner.
            First enter the coords for the upper left corner of your rectangular,
            starting with the horizontal value at the first requester and then
            by entering the vertical value to the second one. After that do the
            same for the coords of the lower right corner.

            @{b}2.@{ub} circle areas
            To create a circle area, enter the horizontal and the vertical
            coord of the circle center. Then enter the radius to the third
            requester.

            @{b}3.@{ub} polygon areas
            Enter to the first requester how many corners your polygon area
            should have. After that you will be asked for the horizontal and
            vertical coords of each corner.

          After defining an area, you can specify a link to be followed, when
          this area of your image is clicked. First, select the type of your
          link from the following list. Included is a small example for the
          type:

             (1) - local anchor               "#marker_at_same_document"
             (2) - local file                 "file_at_same_hd"
             (3) - local file with anchor     "file_at_same_hd.html#mark"
             (4) - absolute file              "file://localhost/file"
             (5) - absolute file with anchor  "file://localhost/file.html#mark"
             (6) - universal WWW              "http://www.server.de/file"
             (7) - universal WWW with anchor  "http://www.server.de/file.html#mark"
             (8) - universal FTP              "ftp://ftp.server.org/"
             (9) - universal Telnet           "telnet://unix.host.org/"
            (10) - universal Gopher           "gopher://gopher.server.org/"
            (11) - universal Usenet           "news:alt.amiga.software.ced_html"
            (12) - universal e-Mail           "mailto:gates@hell.com"

          At the second requester enter the address to link to. The address
          has to match the link type you selected and you don't need to enter
          the addressing theme since the script will do this for you.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
         You can also use this script just to insert the <MAP> tags and maybe
         the <IMG> to use with your map. If you did not insert an image with
         this script, you can use the @{" Image " link "image"} script afterwards, which
         optional asks you for the map name directly.

         If you did not define any sensible areas or even need to add more,
         you can use the @{" Map sensible area " link "area"} script to add more <AREA> tags
         to your map.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE area "5.23. Map sensible area"

@{b}5.23 Map sensible area@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          23

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate areas to use in image maps and add a link to them.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <AREA SHAPE="RECT" COORDS="0,0,40,40" HREF="http://www.example.org/">
          ---
          <AREA SHAPE="CIRCLE" COORDS="40,40,30" HREF="next.html#chapter5">
          ---
          <AREA SHAPE="POLYGON" COORDS="0,0,0,40,40,40,40,0" HREF="mailto:me@here.org">

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          You will be asked to enter the type and the dimensions of your
          areas. First select the type of your area. Enter "c" for circle
          "r" for rectangular, or "p" for polygon.

            @{b}1.@{ub} rectangular areas:
            If you entered an area to be rectangular, you will be prompted 4
            times to insert the coordinates in pixels for the area. Remember,
            the origin (0,0) of area coords is always at the upper left corner.
            First enter the coords for the upper left corner of your rectangular,
            starting with the horizontal value at the first requester and then
            by entering the vertical value to the second one. After that do the
            same for the coords of the lower right corner.

            @{b}2.@{ub} circle areas
            To create a circle area, enter the horizontal and the vertical
            coord of the circle center. Then enter the radius to the third
            requester.

            @{b}3.@{ub} polygon areas
            Enter to the first requester how many corners your polygon area
            should have. After that you will be asked for the horizontal and
            vertical coords of each corner.

         After defining an area, you can specify a link to be followed, when
         this area of your image is clicked. First, select the type of your
         link from the following list. Included is a small example for the type:

            (1) - local anchor               "#marker_at_same_document"
            (2) - local file                 "file_at_same_hd"
            (3) - local file with anchor     "file_at_same_hd.html#mark"
            (4) - absolute file              "file://localhost/file"
            (5) - absolute file with anchor  "file://localhost/file.html#mark"
            (6) - universal WWW              "http://www.server.de/file"
            (7) - universal WWW with anchor  "http://www.server.de/file.html#mark"
            (8) - universal FTP              "ftp://ftp.server.org/"
            (9) - universal Telnet           "telnet://unix.host.org/"
           (10) - universal Gopher           "gopher://gopher.server.org/"
           (11) - universal Usenet           "news:alt.amiga.software.ced_html"
           (12) - universal e-Mail           "mailto:gates@hell.com"

         At the second requester enter the address to link to. The address
         has to match the link type you selected and you don't need to enter the
         addressing scheme, this will be done by the script.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
         You can generate the <MAP> tags needed for <AREA> using the @{" Map " link "map"} script.

         To insert the code for an image to use with your areas you can make use
         of either the @{" Image " link "image"} script or the @{" Map " link "map"} script (which also generates
         the <MAP> tags).
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE link "5.24. Link"

@{b}5.24 Link@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          24

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Insert a link to the document which may be a text or an image link.
          In second case, the parameters for showing the image can be entered
          directly in the same way the @{" Image " link "image"} script does. You can directly
          select the type of the link, e.g. link to a local document, a document
          somewhere else to access via http, a mail address, a newsgroup...

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <A HREF="http://www.someserver.org/text.html#chapter1">
           Should be modified - Link text
          </A>
          ---
          <A HREF="mailto:la@kai.net">
           <IMG SRC="image.iff" ALT="Here should be an image" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100
           HEIGHT=100 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
          </A>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          A requester will ask you for the type of your link, which you can
          select by entering one of the following numbers. A short example is
          also added to show you the result:

            (1) - local anchor               "#marker_at_same_document"
            (2) - local file                 "file_at_same_hd"
            (3) - local file with anchor     "file_at_same_hd.html#mark"
            (4) - absolute file              "file://localhost/file"
            (5) - absolute file with anchor  "file://localhost/file.html#mark"
            (6) - universal WWW              "http://www.server.de/file"
            (7) - universal WWW with anchor  "http://www.server.de/file.html#mark"
            (8) - universal FTP              "ftp://ftp.server.org/"
            (9) - universal Telnet           "telnet://unix.host.org/"
           (10) - universal Gopher           "gopher://gopher.server.org/"
           (11) - universal Usenet           "news:alt.amiga.software.ced_html"
           (12) - universal e-Mail           "mailto:gates@hell.com"

         At the second requester enter the address to link to. The address
         has to match the link type you selected and you don't need to enter the
         addressing scheme, this will be done by the script.

         Then you will be asked whether the link should be a text link or an
         image link. By entering "t" you select a text link type. A small text
         will be inserted and the script stops here. When typing "i" for image
         instead, more requesters will ask you to insert the parameters for the
         image:

         Enter "l", "a" or "u" to the first image requester to tell the script
         whether the path to the image is local, absolute or universal.

         Then enter the path to the image which has to match the path type you
         selected before.

         The next requester asks you for the text which should be shown instead
         of the picture, when image loading is switched off or a text browser is
         used.

         Then you will be asked if you would like to modify the options for the
         image size. You may enter "y" if you want to do this, "n" if you do not
         want to enter any size options to the <IMG> tag or "d" to use the
         following default values:

                  WIDTH="100"
                  HEIGHT="100"
                  BORDER="0"

         If you entered "y" before, you will be asked to enter the image width
         in pixels, the image height in pixels and a border width in pixels.

         The next requester asks if you wish to modify the options for the image
         position. Again you can enter "y", "n" or "d". The default values are:

                  no align
                  HSPACE=10
                  VSPACE=10

         If you entered "y" you can select between left, right, center or no
         alignment by typing the first letter. Then you can enter the horizontal
         and vertical space in pixels between the image and the next elements of
         the document.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE image "5.25. Image"

@{b}5.25 Image@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          25

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate the code for inserting an image to the document, allowing
          several parameters like size and position to be entered directly.
          Optional, use this image with a map.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <IMG SRC="image.iff" ALT="Here should be an image" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100
          HEIGHT=100 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
          ---
          <CENTER>
           <IMG USEMAP="#mymap" SRC="image.iff" ALT="Here should be an image"
           BORDER=0 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=100 ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=10 VSPACE=10>
          </CENTER>
          ---
          <IMG SRC="Image" ALT="text" BORDER=0 WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=100 HSPACE=10
          VSPACE=10 ISMAP>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
         First you will be asked if you wish to use the image just as a
         picture or with a map. Press either "d" for default, "f" for
         an offline map or "n" for an online map (a CGIScript). If you
         selected offline map, enter the name of the map to use at
         the following requester. If you selected online map, the keyword
         ISMAP will be added to the <IMG> tag.

         Enter "l", "a" or "u" to the next image requester to tell the
         script whether the path to the image is local, absolute or
         universal.

         Then enter the path to the image which has to match the path
         type you selected before.

         The next requester asks you for the text which should be shown
         instead of the picture, when image loading is switched off or a
         text browser is used.

         Then you will be asked if you would like to modify the options
         for the image size. You may enter "y" if you want to do this,
         "n" if you do not want to enter any size options to the <IMG>
         tag or "d" to use the following default values:

                  WIDTH="100"
                  HEIGHT="100"
                  BORDER="0"

         If you entered "y" before, you will be asked to enter the image
         width in pixels, the image height in pixels and a border width
         in pixels.

         The next requester asks if you wish to modify the options for
         the image position. Again you can enter "y", "n" or "d". The
         default values are:

                  no align
                  HSPACE="10"
                  VSPACE="10"

         If you entered "y" you can choose between left, right, center or
         no alignment by typing the first letter. Then you can enter the
         horizontal and vertical space in pixels between the image and the
         next elements of the document.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
         When you use this script to insert a picture which should also use
         an image map, you can make use of the @{" Map " link "map"} script to generate the
         map for it. This one also has the possibility to insert images, so it
         might be the better choice for a quick success.

         If you don't need a map for your image, but would like to add a link
         to it, this can be done easily by using the @{" Link " link "link"} script instead
         of the image script. The link script will generate the code for a
         link and also the image, just like this script does.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE formular "5.26. Formular"

@{b}5.26 Formular@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          26

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
           Generate header and footer for a form with all kind of ACTION
           and METHOD options available. Optional generate submit and reset
           buttons.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <FORM ACTION=http://my-url.net/my.script?options METHOD=GET ENCTYPE="text/plain">
            Should be modified - Formular
          </FORM>
          ---
          <FORM ACTION=mailto:locutus@b.org METHOD=POST ENCTYPE="text/plain">
            Should be modified - Formular
            <INPUT TYPE=SUBMIT VALUE=Open_Channel>
            <INPUT TYPE=RESET VALUE=Assimilate>
          </FORM>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          The first requester will ask you for the sending method. You can
          either choose "g" for the get method (e.g. execute a cgi) or "p" for
          the post method (e.g. send a mail).

          If you selected the get method you will be asked to enter "l", "a" or
          "u" for a local, absolute or universal path type and the name of
          the file (probably a CGIscript which may be followed by options). If
          you have chosen the post method you will be prompted for a mail address
          directly.

          You will be asked if you wish to generate submit and reset buttons
          for your form. Enter either "y" or "n".

          If you entered "y" you will be prompted for the texts of your buttons.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          If you decided not to generate buttons for your form with this script,
          you can use the @{" Formular button " link "button"} script later on to insert them
          afterwards.

@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE single "5.27. Formular line"

@{b}5.27 Formular line@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          27

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate a single line text input field to use with a form.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <INPUT NAME=my_name TYPE=TEXT SIZE=20 MAXLENGTH=100>
          ---
          <INPUT NAME=another_name TYPE=DATE SIZE=9 MAXLENGTH=9>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          Give a NAME to your input field which is also the name of the data
          field in the form output (which you might want to process later) by
          entering it to the first requester.

          You can limit the real input length with the next requester. You can
          enter any values from "0" to "32768", default is "10".

          The next requester allows you to define the visuable length of your
          input field. Values are same as above, default is "5".

          Then select the type of your input field by pressing the first
          character of "text", "integer", "float", "date", "URL" or "password".
          Text and password will not be checked by the browser, password type
          fields however will show "*" instead of the entered chars. All other
          types will perform a little check, whether a correct type of input
          was entered.

          If you entered an integer or float type, you will be prompted in
          addition with two requesters asking for minimum and maximum values
          your input field should accept.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          <INPUT> fields can only be used within <FORM> ... </FORM> tags. You
          can generate them using the @{" Formular " link "formular"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE several "5.28. Formular block"

@{b}5.28 Formular block@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          28

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate a text input area to use in forms.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <TEXTAREA NAME=a_name_for_it ROWS=5 COLS=6>
            Should be modified - Default text
          </TEXTAREA>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          At the first requester enter a name for this data field.

          Then enter the number of lines your text area should have. Valid
          values are from "0" to "32768", the default is "5".

          The third requester prompts you for the number of columns, your text
          area should have. Valid values are same as above, the default is "60".

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          <TEXTAREA> fields can only be used within <FORM> ... </FORM> tags. You
          can generate them using the @{" Formular " link "formular"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE formlist "5.29. Formular list"

@{b}5.29 Formular list@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          29

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate a multi-selection field for use in forms.

  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <SELECT NAME=name_for_this SIZE=5>
            <OPTION>
              <!-- Comment - Input 1 -->
              Should be modified
            </OPTION>
            <OPTION SELECTED>
              <!-- Comment - Input 2 -->
              Should be modified
            </OPTION>
           ...
          </SELECT>
          ---
          <SELECT NAME=anderer_name SIZE=2 MULTIPLE>
            <OPTION SELECTED>
              <!-- Comment - Input 1 -->
              Should be modified
            </OPTION>
           ...
          </SELECT>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          At first you will be prompted to enter a NAME for the selection
          field.

          The next requester asks you for the number of inputs for your
          multi-selection field. This is how many options can be selected
          by the user. Valid values are from "0" to "32768", the default
          is "5".

          A third requester asks if multiple selections should be made
          possible. Enter "y" or "n" (default).

          For each input item a requester will pop up to ask you, if the
          input should be preselected, when the page comes up. Again, enter
          "y" or "n". You can choose only one item to be preselected when
          you did not allow multiple selections.

  @{b}Notes:@{ub}
          Multi-selection fields can only be used within <FORM> ... </FORM>
          tags. You can generate them using the @{" Formular " link "formular"} script.

          The way multi-selection fields are shown is very different from
          browser to browser. Some show them as cycle menus, some as small
          lists with scrollbar, others offer both options (user definable or
          depending on the number of inputs given - some browsers switch from
          menu to list, if there are more then 4 <OPTION> tags).
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE button "5.30. Formular button"

@{b}5.30 Formular button@{ub}

  @{b}Number:@{ub}
          30

  @{b}Purpose:@{ub}
          Generate radio, checkbox, submit or reset buttons for a form.
  @{b}Output:@{ub}
          <INPUT TYPE=RADIO NAME=Select_one VALUE=Entry1>
          ---
          <INPUT TYPE=CHECKBOX NAME=Select_one_or_more VALUE=Entry2>
          ---
          <INPUT TYPE=SUBMIT VALUE=Send_something>
          ---
          <INPUT TYPE=RESET VALUE=Clear_all>

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}
          You will be prompted which kind of button you want to generate.
          You can select "s" for radio buttons with only one single input
          per group allowed, "m" for a group of checkboxes with multible
          selections possible, "v" for a validate (submit) button type and
          "r" for a reset button.

          If you selected a radio or checkbox button type, you will be asked
          for the number of buttons to be generated. Valid are all numbers
          from "1" to "32768", the default is "3".

          If you selected to generate the code for a submit or reset button,
          you will be prompted to enter the text for this button. The script
          will end here.

          If you selected radio or checkbox buttons, some more requester will
          appear, first asking you for a text string for each button, then
          for the value of each button and finally the name for this group of
          buttons.

  @{b}Note:@{ub}
          Buttons can only be used within <FORM> ... </FORM> tags. You can
          generate them using the @{" Formular " link "formular"} script.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE glossar "6. Glossary"

@{b}6. Glossary@{ub}

  In this chapter you can find some background informations about notions used
  in this documentation:

    @{" #RGB      " link "rgb"       } Notes about color schemes
    @{" Path type " link "path"      } The different types of file paths explained
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE rgb "6.01. #RGB"

@{b}6.01 #RGB@{ub}

  Several scripts of CED_HTML allow you to change the color of a HTML
  element and ask you to enter a #RGB color code.

  You always need to enter the leading "#" before typing the hexadecimal
  values for red, green and blue, otherwise the color code will not be
  recognized by your browser.

  Since the CED_HTML scripts always insert exactly what you typed into the
  requester, you may also use the color names some browsers understand and
  replace them with predefined RGB values, e.g. "white", "red" or "magenta".
  When doing so, please remember, that predefined colors are not part of the
  HTML v3.2 standard and may not be interpreted by all browser programs.
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE path "6.02. Path type"
@NEXT todo

@{b}6.02 Path type@{ub}

  Some scripts of CED_HTML ask you to enter the path to an other HTML file,
  an image or another file type. Before you can do so, you often will be
  asked for the type of path you wish to enter. Depending on the type you
  entered, the CED_HTML scripts will insert the addressing scheme needed for
  this kind of path.

  In general path types can be "local" (files at the same server, addressed
  with a relative path), "absolute" (files at the same server, addressed with a
  full path) or "universal" (files at any server, addressed via http).

  When you are asked for the path to an image or CGIscript, only these three
  addressing schemes are allowed. Formulars in addition can have e-mail
  addresses as input.

  When generating links with CED_HTML many more options are available. You can
  always select the three main addressing schemes together with anchors and
  path types can also be e-mail addresses, newsgroups, ftp servers and so on.

  Here is an overview of the addressing schemes you will find in the scripts:

    @{" Local anchor              " link "la"     } "#marker_at_same_document"
    @{" Local file                " link "lf"     } "file_at_same_hd"
    @{" Local file with anchor    " link "lfa"    } "file_at_same_hd.html#mark"
    @{" Absolute file             " link "af"     } "file://localhost/file"
    @{" Absolute file with anchor " link "afa"    } "file://localhost/file.html#mark"
    @{" Universal WWW             " link "uw"     } "http://www.server.de/file."
    @{" Universal WWW with anchor " link "uwa"    } "http://www.server.de/file.html#mark"
    @{" Universal FTP             " link "ftp"    } "ftp://ftp.server.org/"
    @{" Universal Telnet          " link "telnet" } "telnet://unix.host.org/"
    @{" Universal Gopher          " link "gopher" } "gopher://gopher.server.org/"
    @{" Universal Usenet          " link "news"   } "news:alt.amiga.software.ced_html"
    @{" Universal e-Mail          " link "mail"   } "mailto:gates@hell.com"
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE la "6.02.01. Local anchor"

@{b}6.02.01 Local anchor@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Marker in the current HTML document itself. Only works with links.

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <A HREF="#marker_at_this_document">
          ---
          <A HREF="#top_of_page">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE lf "6.02.02. Local file"

@{b}6.02.02 Local file@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          File at the same hard drive, given with its relative path. The
          file does not have to be in the same directory. Works with links,
          images, CGIscripts and so on.

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <IMG SRC="image.gif">
          ---
          <A HREF="sub_dir/next_page.html">
          ---
          <FORM METHOD=GET ACTION="../another_dir/form.cgi?options">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE lfa "6.02.03. Local file with anchor"

@{b}6.02.03 Local file with anchor@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Marker in another HTML document at the same hard drive, given
          with its relative path. The file does not have to be in the same
          directory. Only works with links.

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <A HREF="doc.html#part3">
          ---
          <A HREF="../another_dir/doc.html#message3">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE af "6.02.04. Absolute file"

@{b}6.02.04 Absolute file@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          A local file at the same host with an absolute path.

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <A HREF="file://localhost/hard_drive:dir/amiga.html">
          ---
          <IMG SRC="file://localhost/sub_dir/image.jpg">
          ---
          <FORM METHOD=GET ACTION="file://localhost/hard_drive:dir/form.cgi?options">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE afa "6.02.05. Absolute file with anchor"

@{b}6.02.05 Absolute file with anchor@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          A HTML document at the same host with an absolute path and an anchor.

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="file://localhost/hard_drive:dir/doc.html#mark">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE uw "6.02.10. Universal WWW"

@{b}6.02.10 Universal WWW@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          File at any server, given with its universal path and addressed with
          "http://".

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <A HREF="http://www.server.de/path/doc.html">
          ---
          <IMG SRC="http://www.example.org/pictures/mail-anim.gif">
          ---
          <FORM METHOD=GET ACTION="http://www.cgi.org/cgi/form.cgi?options">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE uwa "6.02.11. Universal WWW with anchor"

@{b}6.02.11 Universal WWW with anchor@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          HTML document with a marker at any server, given with its universal
          path and addressed with "http://".

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="http://www.server.de/path/doc.html#mark">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE ftp "6.02.12. Universal FTP"

@{b}6.02.12 Universal FTP@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Link to a ftp server. If the browser has an internal ftp program or
          is able to use an external one, a connection to a file server can be
          made directly.

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="ftp://ftp.server.org/">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE telnet "6.02.13. Universal Telnet"

@{b}6.02.13 Universal Telnet@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Can be used for links. If the browser has an internal telnet program
          or is able to use an external one, a telnet connection to an unix
          server can be opened.

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="telnet://unix.host.org/">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE gopher "6.02.14. Universal Gopher"

@{b}6.02.14 Universal Gopher@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Can be used for links. If the browser is able to use an internal or
          external gopher program, a connection to a gopher service can be
          opened.

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="gopher://gopher.server.org/">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE news "6.02.15. Universal Usenet"

@{b}6.02.15 Universal Usenet@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Can be used for links. If the browser has an internal or external news
          program and also access to a news server, usenet newsgroups can be read
          by following the link.

  @{b}Example:@{ub}
          <A HREF="news:alt.amiga.software.ced_html">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE mail "6.02.16. Universal e-mail"

@{b}6.02.16 Universal e-mail@{ub}

  @{b}Meaning:@{ub}
          Write an e-mail to a mail address. Can be used for links and forms.

  @{b}Examples:@{ub}
          <A HREF="mailto:gates@hell.com">
          ---
          <FORM METHOD=POST ACTION="mailto:my@mail-address.org">
@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE todo "7. Bugs / Todo"

@{b}7. Bugs / Todo@{ub}


  * Iso Latin 1

    The @{" Iso latin 1 " link "iso"} script could still be improved to check whether
    the char to be replaced is part of a HTML tag, so &, %, <, >, ", ~ and
    other chars which might be used in them can be replaced in the text, but
    not within a tag where they are needed as part of the HTML language and
    replacing them would screw up the document. At the moment replacement of
    these chars is disabled at all.

    Anybody has a good idea, how to check for HTML commands safely?


  * Documentation

    Translate this doc to French and German.


  * Installer script

    It would be pretty cool to add the cedmacros.ced script to CygnusED's
